# The `SmallPtrSetImplBase` Class Reference

<DoxygenPage pluginConfig={pluginConfig}>

## Description {#details}

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/smallptrsetimplbase">SmallPtrSetImplBase</a> - This is the common code shared among all the <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/smallptrset">SmallPtrSet&lt;&gt;</a>&#39;s, which is almost everything.

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/smallptrset">SmallPtrSet</a> has two modes, one for small and one for large sets.

Small sets use an array of pointers allocated in the <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/smallptrset">SmallPtrSet</a> object, which is treated as a simple array of pointers. When a pointer is added to the set, the array is scanned to see if the element already exists, if not the element is &#39;pushed back&#39; onto the array. If we run out of space in the array, we grow into the &#39;large set&#39; case. <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/smallset">SmallSet</a> should be used when the sets are often small. In this case, no memory allocation is used, and only light-weight and cache-efficient scanning is used.

Large sets use a classic exponentially-probed hash table. Empty buckets are represented with an illegal pointer value (-1) to allow null pointers to be inserted. Tombstones are represented with another illegal pointer value (-2), to allow deletion. The hash table is resized when the table is 3/4 or more. When this happens, the table is doubled in size.

Definition at line 52 of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/smallptrset-h">SmallPtrSet.h</a>.

Number of elements in CurArray that contain a value or are a tombstone.

If small, all these elements are at the beginning of CurArray and the rest is uninitialized.
